[[Image:BRCA Genes-location of BRCA1 and BRCA2 on chromosomes 13 and 17.gif|right]]

'''BRCA1''' ('''breast cancer 1, early onset''') is a [[human]] [[gene]] that belongs to a class of genes known as [[tumor suppressor gene]]s. Like many other tumor suppressor genes, BRCA1 regulates the cycle of cell division by keeping cells from growing and dividing too rapidly or in an uncontrolled way. In particular, it inhibits the growth of cells that line the [[milk duct]]s in the [[breast]].

The protein made by the BRCA1 gene is directly involved in the repair of damaged [[DNA]]. In the nucleus of many types of normal cells, the BRCA1 protein interacts with the protein produced by the [[RAD51]] gene to mend breaks in DNA. These breaks can be caused by natural radiation or other exposures, but also occur when chromosomes exchange genetic material in preparation for cell division. The [[BRCA2]] protein, which has a function similar to that of BRCA1, also interacts with the RAD51 protein. By repairing DNA, these three proteins play a role in maintaining the stability of the human genome.

Research suggests that both the BRCA1 and BRCA2 proteins regulate the activity of other genes and play a critical role in embryo development. The BRCA1 protein probably interacts with many other proteins, including tumor suppressors and regulators of the cell division cycle.

The BRCA1 gene is located on the long (q) arm of [[chromosome 17 (human)|chromosome 17]] at position 21, from [[base pair]] 38,449,843 to base pair 38,530,933.

==Related conditions==
Certain variations of the BRCA1 gene lead to an increased risk for [[breast cancer]]. Researchers have identified more than 600 [[mutation]]s in the BRCA1 gene, many of which are associated with an increased risk of cancer. These mutations can be changes in one or a small number of DNA [[base pair]]s (the building blocks of DNA). In some cases, large segments of DNA are rearranged. A mutated BRCA1 gene usually makes a [[protein]] that does not function properly because it is abnormally short. Researchers believe that the defective BRCA1 protein is unable to help fix mutations that occur in other genes. These defects accumulate and may allow cells to grow and divide uncontrollably to form a tumor.

In addition to breast cancer, mutations in the BRCA1 gene also increase the risk of [[ovarian cancer|ovarian]], [[prostate cancer|prostate]] and [[colon cancer]]s.

==KU0058684, a promising treatment for breast cancer patients with BRCA defects==
The physicians motto from year gone by still rings true today, “kill the cancer before you kill the patient”. To the present day treatments for cancer are only derivatives of the old. They are still highly toxic because they are nonspecific agents. However, with the study of biochemical pathways and genetic analysis, new treatments for cancer will have a higher specificity to cancer cells, hence less toxicity to the patients. In those terms KU0058684 is the treatment of the future. 
	KU0058684 is a small-molecule PARP inhibitor that, when applied to a culture with BRCA1 or BRCA2 defective cells, decreases the total number of possible cellular growth by nearly 70%. In addition, when the same concentration of KU0058684 is applied to a culture of wild type cells it only inhibits roughly 30% of cellular growth, which indicates that KU0058684 in not significantly toxic to normal cells because it is specific to a phenotype caused by BRCA defective cells (Farmer et al). 
The BRCA defect that gives rise to the specificity of KU0058684 is the loss of heterozygosity to form homozygous recessive BRCA in somatic cells. The production of a -/- results in the loss of the BRCA gene-product(s), which is essential to the homologous repair mechanism because it is needed to form Rad51 protein which allows the sister chromatid to invade (Bhattacharyya et al). The resulting loss of functional double strand break (DSB) repair mechanism leaves the cell vulnerable to DSB which after multiple replications might result in a cell without growth control, hence cancer.  
	Note that the loss of BRCA gene results in the inability to efficiently correct DSB. Similarly, the loss of functional Poly ADP-ribose polymerase (PARP) results in the inability to effectively repair single strand break (SSB) (Schultz et al).
If these breaks are not fixed, as is the case if PARP is inhibited, then SSB might transform into a DSB at the S phase of the cell cycle. Once the DSB forms it would have to under go the relatively error free homologous recombination repair, which is not available in a BRCA defective cell, or the error prone end joining repair. Hence, DSB are either repaired by end annealing or not repaired at all. This would yield cellular arrest at the G2/M checkpoint. Upon which, apoptosis occurs (Farmer et al). 
The phenotype of active or inactive DSB repair is the point of specificity for the KU0058684 treatment. In short, this treatment is not only limited to BRCA homozygous patients but any patient who’s cancer cells are marked with the inactive DSB repair mechanism.


